{
  "issue_summary": "The enterprise database infrastructure experienced a severe transport layer degradation due to an unmanaged database synchronization storm following a storage controller outage. When the storage subsystem was returned to service after an extended period of downtime, the core database nodes instantly initiated massive, parallel cross-region data synchronization tasks to clear transaction backlogs. This unthrottled data stream completely saturated the available capacity of our primary core network transit paths, pushing link utilization to 100%. The resulting interface congestion triggered extensive tail-drops that reach 81% across identity segments, which discarded outbound single sign-on security assertion frames and caused downstream transaction failures.",
  "five_why_analysis": [
    {
      "question": "1. Why did the high-level application failure block the business workflow?",
      "answer": "The business workflow was blocked because external cloud applications could not validate incoming user access credentials. The single sign-on platform failed to complete authentication requests because the required token data was missing."
    },
    {
      "question": "2. Why did the application layer or infrastructure nodes fail to process transactions or handle authentication?",
      "answer": "The network edge failed to deliver data frames because the outbound internet circuit was fully saturated. This congestion triggered aggressive tail-drops that discarded outbound single sign-on validation frames."
    },
    {
      "question": "3. Why was this exact systemic dependency, resource limitation, or cryptographic incompatibility not mitigated before production exposure?",
      "answer": "This data synchronization storm was not mitigated because the high-availability database cluster lacked integrated traffic throttling policies for post-downtime recovery modes. The application design allowed unthrottled replication loops when clearing transaction backlogs."
    },
    {
      "question": "4. Why did proactive automation validation, change window testing, or secondary workarounds fail to catch or stop this configuration drift?",
      "answer": "The operational recovery playbooks verified database integrity steps but omitted requirements to validate active bandwidth limits or cross-functional network capacity checks before re-initializing replication links."
    },
    {
      "question": "5. Why was a permanent architectural upgrade, automated mapping, or infrastructure redundancy not successfully implemented beforehand?",
      "answer": "An automated traffic-throttling verification mechanism was missing from our incident recovery procedures. Application modifications were executed manually without an automated validation loop to match data generation against network interface baselines."
    }
  ],
  "root_cause_summary": {
    "statement": "The definitive root cause of this incident was an unmanaged database synchronization storm following a storage controller outage, driven by unthrottled post-downtime recovery profiles inside the high-availability replication cluster. When the storage subsystem recovered, the database nodes initiated massive, parallel cross-region data transfers that fully saturated core network circuit bandwidth, forcing routing interfaces into persistent tail-drop routines that discarded high-priority single sign-on validation frames. The operational recovery playbooks failed to catch this risk because they omitted application-level traffic throttling constraints from the database re-initialization workflow. To permanently resolve this vulnerability class, the enterprise must apply strict recovery traffic controls. This includes configuring explicit bandwidth ceilings within database replication engines and implementing automated network-capacity checks during post-downtime recovery operations.",
    "root_cause_category": "Network / Traffic Overload (Application Storm)"
  }
}

TASK: GENERATE CAPA

Problem Description:
The enterprise remote access framework experienced a critical authentication failure across global software-defined network paths. On June 19, 2026, following the expansion of corporate security group nesting, user authentication tokens expanded dramatically in size. When remote endpoints attempted logons over secure IPsec VPN tunnels, the large Kerberos Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT) payloads forced network packets to exceed standard Maximum Transmission Unit (MTU) boundaries. Because the default Kerberos protocol configuration utilized User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for packet transfer, the underlying network routers fragmented the oversized tokens. Intermediate security firewalls along the transit path were configured to drop fragmented UDP packets to prevent IP fragmentation exploits. Consequently, the fragmented Kerberos pre-authentication requests were systematically dropped before reaching the regional Key Distribution Centers (KDCs). This resulted in continuous connection timeouts on client devices, blocking remote access until the protocol transport mechanism was programmatically shifted to Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).

Business Impact:
- The secure remote access gateways were entirely blocked from validating inbound client authentication requests, halting remote administration operations globally.
- The integration pipelines inside the secondary testing and staging sandboxes failed completely due to secure remote execution shell timeouts across fragmented network paths.
- Over 75,000 automated field data transfers and synchronization tasks were dropped or timed out over a 6-hour window, resulting in severe supply chain reporting delays.
- The network packet fragmentation issue directly blocked secure operational access for approximately 18,500 remote engineering and administrative users during critical business hours.

Technical Investigation:
[19-06-2026 08:30:00 AM] Network edge monitors signaled a major drop in successful user VPN authentication rates, accompanied by sharp spikes in connection timeout alerts.
[19-06-2026 09:00:00 AM] The Network Operations Center initiated an emergency bridge call with the Identity Management and Core Routing teams to trace the authentication path.
[19-06-2026 09:45:00 AM] Engineers executed network packet captures using Wireshark on the external interfaces of the Domain Controllers and noted an absolute absence of port 88 UDP packets from affected remote clients.
[19-06-2026 10:30:00 AM] Network security analysts ran firewall log parsing queries, revealing thousands of dropped packet logs referencing 'IP fragmentation exploit protection trigger' matching remote client source IPs.
[19-06-2026 11:15:00 AM] Triage teams cross-referenced directory changes and confirmed that recent security updates under CHG0047211 nested users into extensive resource groups, driving individual token sizes above 1,500 bytes.
[19-06-2026 12:00:00 PM] Diagnostic analysis confirmed that the VPN tunnel overhead reduced the effective MTU to 1,400 bytes, forcing the oversized UDP Kerberos tokens to fragment at the gateway router.
[19-06-2026 12:45:00 PM] The engineering team drafted an emergency Group Policy template modification patch to lower the enterprise Kerberos UDP packet size threshold to enforce TCP fallback.
[19-06-2026 01:30:00 PM] Engineers deployed a registry configuration override setting 'MaxPacketSize' to a decimal value of 1 under 'HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Lsa\Kerberos\Parameters'.
[19-06-2026 02:00:00 PM] The updated policy configuration was synchronized across all regional Domain Controllers, forcing the KDC engine to mandate stream-oriented TCP port 88 transfers for all tokens.
[19-06-2026 02:15:00 PM] Remote client devices successfully authenticated over the VPN tunnels, establishing stable connections with zero packet fragmentation drops observed at the firewall layer.
[19-06-2026 02:30:00 PM] Operational authentication metrics completely stabilized, and the incident bridge officially handed the record over to Problem Management for comprehensive root cause tracking.

Approved Root Cause:
