  "issue_summary": "The enterprise remote access framework experienced a critical authentication failure across global software-defined network paths. On June 19, 2026, following the expansion of corporate security group nesting, user authentication tokens expanded dramatically in size. When remote endpoints attempted logons over secure IPsec VPN tunnels, the large Kerberos Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT) payloads forced network packets to exceed standard Maximum Transmission Unit (MTU) boundaries. Because the default Kerberos protocol configuration utilized User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for packet transfer, the underlying network routers fragmented the oversized tokens. Intermediate security firewalls along the transit path were configured to drop fragmented UDP packets to prevent IP fragmentation exploits. Consequently, the fragmented Kerberos pre-authentication requests were systematically dropped before reaching the regional Key Distribution Centers (KDCs). This resulted in continuous connection timeouts on client devices, blocking remote access until the protocol transport mechanism was programmatically shifted to Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).",
