    "statement": "The definitive root cause of this incident was a protocol transport configuration mismatch where large Kerberos tokens were transmitted via User Datagram Protocol over an MTU-constrained VPN path, triggering dropping actions at the firewall layer. Group expansion change CHG0047211 drove individual token sizes past standard packet thresholds. When users logged on remotely, the additional encapsulation overhead of the IPsec VPN tunnel split these large UDP packets into multiple smaller fragments. Because core network firewalls run strict security baselines designed to drop fragmented UDP datagrams to block teardrop exploits, the authentication stream was severed in transit. Pre-production staging failed to highlight this dependency because test zones did not mirror the complex WAN routing profiles or tunnel restrictions present in the production fabric. To permanently neutralize this class of vulnerability, a comprehensive architectural transformation is required to shift core authentication traffic away from volatile datagram transport. Moving forward, the global enterprise group policy baseline must explicitly mandate stream-based TCP encapsulation for all Kerberos transactions across all corporate domains.",
    "root_cause_category": "Configuration"
