    {
      "action_type": "PA",
      "action_description": "The Enterprise Infrastructure Architecture group implemented a permanent governance upgrade to the network edge provisioning guidelines to prevent future fragmentation-induced authentication failures. A mandatory network profile standard was established across all core firewalls to carefully whitelist fragmented packets specifically when negotiating with known, trusted corporate KDC ip ranges. Automated monitoring rules were built within Datadog to continuously trace the ratio of UDP versus TCP Kerberos transactions, instantly alerting operations teams if packet sizes trend near critical limits. Pre-production testing sandboxes were updated to include a simulated WAN latency and MTU constraint validation grid to ensure future group updates undergo strict validation checks. Finally, official security hardening guidelines and directory deployment handbooks were updated to mandate TCP transport configurations for all newly deployed external network domains.",
      "action_owner": "Network Security & Core Architecture Team"
    }
  ],
  "lessons_learned": [
    "Future architectural expansions and security group modifications must treat network transport layers as highly dynamic dependencies that directly impact authentication success rates. Relying on legacy datagram transport across encrypted multi-provider networks introduces significant packet drop risks that must be systematically bypassed via mandatory stream-oriented protocol enforcement."
  ]
}

